## Step 5 (workflow §7.5) — Decomposition of IZ upstairs

**Slice probe (`stage3b_IZ_slice_decomp.out.txt`):** `IZ + sliceA` at
N = (4,8,12,20) has a **single minimal prime** upstairs (ambient codim 10,
degree **64** — equal to the symbolic `degree IZ = 64`, so no degree is lost
and nothing splits on this slice). Its prime presentation on the slice:

```
(N4−20, N3−12, N2−8, N1−4, 4M−e1(w),
 w3²−w4²+256, w2²−w4²+336, w1²−w4²+384, u−w4²+400,
 8J² − e4(w) − w4²·(w1w2+w1w3+w2w3) − w4³·(w1+w2+w3) − w4⁴
     + 400·e2(w) + 800w4² − 152320)
```

This is strong evidence the rotating difference divisor is **irreducible on the
incidence cover** over the generic base.

**Full symbolic decomposition (`stage3_IZ_decomp.out.txt`): IZ is prime.**
`minimalPrimes IZ` returns exactly one prime and `primaryDecomposition IZ`
exactly one primary component, both equal to IZ itself (codim 6, degree 64):

```
(4M − e1(w),
 N4² + u − w4²,  N3² + u − w3²,  N2² + u − w2²,  N1² + u − w1²,
 N1N2N3N4 + 8J² − u² − u·e2(w) − e4(w))
```

The last generator is −delta/2 reduced mod IX (delta = −2·(P + 8J² − u² −
u·e2 − e4)). So the rotating difference divisor is **irreducible and reduced
on the incidence cover**: it contributes a single node to the realization
poset with no splitting to track.

